Ans.

‚öôÔ∏è Step 1: BOM (Bill of Materials)
A BOM is the foundation of everything in manufacturing.

It defines:
- The finished item (the product you‚Äôll make)
- The raw materials needed
- The quantities of each raw material

Optional: operations, workstations, and costs


üß© Step 2: Production Plan ‚Üí BOM linkage
When you create a Production Plan, you select:
- The items to manufacture
- The quantity to produce
- Optionally, the sales orders to fulfill

When you click ‚ÄúGet Items from BOM‚Äù, ERPNext:
- Looks up the default BOM for each production item (from the Item master or you manually select it).
-  Links that BOM to the Production Plan record (in child table Production Plan Item).
- Multiplies the BOM raw materials by the quantity to produce to calculate total material requirements.

Step 3: Get Raw Materials (the magic button)

Step 4: Downstream Effects
- From the Production Plan, you can then:
- Create Material Requests (for purchase/transfer)
- Create Work Orders
- Both will carry forward those raw materials and BOM links.

real workflow :

| Step                      | Action                                  | Where the data comes from                      |
| ------------------------- | --------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Create BOM                | Define finished product + raw materials | `tabBOM` + `tabBOM Item`                       |
| Create Production Plan    | Link item ‚Üí default BOM                 | `Production Plan Item` child table             |
| Click "Get Raw Materials" | Pulls from BOM using backend function   | `get_bom_items_as_dict()`                      |
| Materials show up         | Summed + merged list of all RM          | `Production Plan Material Request` child table |



